title: perf test runner: support NCHW->NHWC rotation
body:
1. Support NCHW->NHWC rotation. For some models, they have different input data for ONNX and TF.  Like the mlperf resnet50 model,  the onnx model expects NCHW input but TF expects NHWC.  NHWC is the TensorFlow default, however NCHW is the optimal format for both MKL and CUDNN.  Unless I can get another TF model in NCHW format,  I have to rotate the input by myself.

2.  Previously, the perf test tool only randomly pick one test data set, and repeatedly run with it again and again. This PR will load all the test data sets and do the random choice for each InferenceSession::Run().

title: Support both Scalar tensor and 1-d tensor for Loop iter/cond input
body:
The shape of Loop inputs ```M``` and ```cond```, according to below, could either be a scalar(rank 0), or a 1-d tensor(rank 1), and depending on the actual rank it may produce different outputs for subsequent nodes such as ```Gather```. Thus ORT ```Loop``` operator cannot hard code these inputs to be rank 1. This PR also include some fixes for test failures caused by updating Conv shape inferences in ONNX(https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/1988). 
```
        .Input(
            0,
            "M",
            "A maximum trip-count for the loop specified at runtime. Optional."
            " Pass empty string to skip.",
            "I",
            OpSchema::Optional)
        .Input(
            1,
            "cond",
            "A boolean termination condition. Optional. Pass empty string to skip.",
            "B",
            OpSchema::Optional)
...
        .TypeConstraint(
            "I",
            {"tensor(int64)"},
            "tensor of int64, which should be a scalar.")
        .TypeConstraint(
            "B",
            {"tensor(bool)"},
            "tensor of bool, which should be a scalar.")
```

title: Quantization tool to support quantization of Conv and MatMul nodes.
body:
tool supports quantization of an onnx model. quantize() takes a model in ModelProto format and returns the quantized model in ModelProto format
# Load the onnx model 
model = onnx.load('path/to/the/model.onnx') 
# Quantize 
quantized_model = quantize(model, quantization_mode=QuantizationMode.IntegerOps) 
# Save the quantized model 
onnx.save(quantized_model, 'path/to/the/quantized_model.onnx')

A subgraph may have no inputs (e.g. subgraph in If has no explicit inputs) or value infos (e.g. a subgraph with just an If node in it).

It should always have outputs but in case it doesn't (nothing fails currently if it doesn't even though that makes it meaningless) make sure it has a node if there are no outputs.
